) in Korean culture and society. As the first interdisciplinary work of its kind, it investigates many topics in geomancy studies that have never been previously explored, and contains contributions from a number of disciplines including geography, historical studies, environmental science, architecture, landscape architecture, religious studies, and psychoanalysis. While almost all books in English about geomancy are addressed to general readers as practical guides for divining auspicious locations, P'ungsu is a work of rigorous scholarship that documents, analyzes, and explains past and current practices of geomancy. Its readers will better understand the impact of geomancy on the Korean cultural landscape and appreciate the significant ecological principles embedded in the geomantic traditions of Korea; while researchers will discover new insights and inspirations for future research on geomancy not only in Korea, but in China and elsewhere.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Jun 2024) 0aFeng shuizKorea. 4aAsian Studies : Korean Studies. 4aEnvironmental Studies : Environmental Philosophy. 4aSociology : Geography. 7aHISTORY / Asia / Korea.2bisacsh1 aChoi, Won-Suk, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHyun, Kim Duk, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKang, Cheol Joong, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLee, Dowon, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLee, Hwa, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSung, Jongsang, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aYoon, Hong-Key, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aYoon, Hong-key, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aYoon, Hong-key, eedi